[1]
Date: 28 Apr 2011
Source: Farmers Guardian [edited]
http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/latest-news/100-cows-slaughtered-as-tb-hits-cumbrian-farm/38646.article


100 cows slaughtered as TB hits Cumbrian farm
---------------------------------------------
Cumbrian farmers are on high alert after 100 animals tested positive
for tuberculosis (TB). 80 dairy cows on the farm near Penrith have
already been slaughtered and a further 20 are to be slaughtered next
week.

Spokeswoman from the Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratories Agency
(AHVLA), Caroline Ling, said the agency was notified of the outbreak
when the farmer had 4 of his calves tested last month.

"Bovine TB outbreaks in Cumbria are very rare and there are serious
implications for the cattle owner," she said. "We're pursuing
epidemiological investigations to find where it has come from and
where it has gone to. We're working really hard to locate the source
of infection. We'll do everything we need to find the source of this
disease and that is a priority." She said the farm is running a closed
herd of 500 and there have not been any movements of animals off or
onto the farm recently.

NFU Cumbria county chairman Robert Craig said the outbreak had come
as a huge blow. "This is terrible news for this farming family, and
will come as a shock to farmers across the county and beyond," he
said. "It is important that we wait to hear from Animal Health the
findings of a contiguous test which is currently taking place and
which may provide some clues as to how a closed herd in Cumbria came
to be infected. I would urge everyone to place it in context with what
is happening in other areas of the country. The North West does not
have a problem with TB in its cattle; this type of herd breakdown is
extremely rare."

[Byline: Olivia Midgley]

