Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The identity of the bacterium in the Cumbrian outbreak (likely to be
_Mycobacterium bovis_), as well as the results of the epidemiological
investigation into its route of introduction into the affected farm,
are anticipated with interest.

Badger source is the most likely one, but other potential sources of
infection in Cumbria should not be excluded. According to previously
posted information (archived 20100522.1703), the disease has been
detected in wild boars, as well as in cats, dogs, domestic pigs and
camelids. Those deserve to be taken into consideration in addition to
badgers. - Mod.AS

The interactive HealthMap/ProMED map for England is available at:
http://healthmap.org/r/0MHu - CopyEd.EJP]

[The English Badger(_Meles meles_)is a protected species in the
United Kingdom. Any form of trapping, baiting or hunting of the
English Badger in the UK is illegal.
Photo of English badger:
http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/5/20/1274355370296/Badger-cull-006.jpg
- Mod.JW]]
